#compdef stitchmd
# =============================================================================
# stitchmd — Abhinav Gupta's "Stitch multiple Markdown files
#            together into a single document" — a Go CLI that
#            reads a SUMMARY-style Markdown file containing a
#            hierarchical link-list of other Markdown files and
#            generates a single combined Markdown document with
#            auto-generated table-of-contents, heading-level
#            offsetting, and link rewriting.
#            Distinguishing from mdbook (Rust), pandoc (Haskell
#            multi-format), and other Markdown processors by:
#              - SUMMARY-FILE-DRIVEN — input is a top-level
#                Markdown file with a hierarchical list of links:
#                  # My Book
#                  - [Introduction](intro.md)
#                  - [Chapter 1](chap1/index.md)
#                    - [Section 1.1](chap1/sec1.md)
#                    - [Section 1.2](chap1/sec2.md)
#                  - [Chapter 2](chap2.md)
#                stitchmd resolves the links, inlines their
#                contents, and produces a single output file
#              - HEADING OFFSET via -offset N — adjusts heading
#                levels of inlined files (positive = deeper,
#                negative = shallower) so that chapter
#                hierarchies render correctly:
#                  -offset 2  → chapter file's # becomes ###
#                  -offset -1 → chapter file's ## becomes #
#              - AUTO-GENERATED TOC per section (suppress with
#                -no-toc) — each section gets a `<details>`
#                expandable table of contents
#              - LINK REWRITING — relative links in inlined files
#                are rewritten to point to anchor positions in
#                the combined output (e.g., `(intro.md#section)`
#                becomes `(#intro-section)`)
#              - PREFACE INSERTION via -preface FILE — content
#                inserted verbatim at top of output (license
#                headers, badges, etc.)
#              - DIFF MODE via -d / -diff — show diff between
#                current output file and what would be generated;
#                requires -o; useful for CI to detect outdated
#                docs
#              - COLOR OUTPUT via -color (always|never|auto) —
#                uses mattn/go-colorable + mattn/go-isatty for
#                cross-platform color detection
#              - UNSAFE MODE via -unsafe — allows file references
#                outside the working directory (default off for
#                security)
#              - DIR-CHANGE via -C DIR — sets working directory
#                before resolving file paths
#              - STDIN / STDOUT — FILE='-' reads from stdin;
#                omitted -o writes to stdout; integrates with
#                Unix pipelines
#              - go.abhg.dev MODULE PATH — uses Abhinav's
#                personal-domain module hosting convention
#              - markdownfmt INTEGRATION via Kunde21/
#                markdownfmt — output goes through markdownfmt
#                v3 for canonical Markdown formatting
#            Used by: mdbook authors needing alternate output
#            formats, documentation teams maintaining
#            multi-file Markdown books, and as a reference
#            implementation of yuin/goldmark + Kunde21/
#            markdownfmt + pkg/diff + colorable composition
#            in Go.
#
# Author:  Abhinav Gupta (abhinav on GitHub, abhg.dev) — Go
#          infrastructure engineer at Uber.  Maintains other
#          Go tooling: doc2go (Go documentation generator),
#          restack (git interactive-rebase stacked-PR
#          rebaser), goldmark-* plugins, and more.  License:
#          GPL-2.0 (stitchmd).
# Source:  https://github.com/abhinav/stitchmd
#          https://github.com/abhinav/stitchmd/blob/main/flags.go
#          https://github.com/abhinav/stitchmd/blob/main/usage.txt
#          https://github.com/abhinav/stitchmd/blob/main/go.mod
# CLI:     flags.go — uses Go's stdlib `flag` package (NOT
#          cobra / urfave/cli; minimal binary size).  Headline
#          library: **yuin/goldmark** (goldmark is the new
#          variant being documented here, expanding Axis 19 —
#          Markdown Parsing — to Go).
# Library: github.com/yuin/goldmark v1.8.2
#          ("goldmark" — "A markdown parser written in Go.
#           Easy to extend, standard(CommonMark) compliant,
#           well structured." — Yusuke Inuzuka (yuin on
#           GitHub).  Distinct from pulldown-cmark (R665,
#           Rust Axis 19 opener) and from russross/blackfriday,
#           gomarkdown/markdown, golang-commonmark, and other
#           Go Markdown libraries by being:
#              1. COMMONMARK 0.31 COMPLIANT — passes the full
#                 CommonMark specification's conformance suite.
#                 Distinct from blackfriday (CommonMark
#                 partial), and from gomarkdown/markdown
#                 (CommonMark close but not 100%).  goldmark
#                 is the RECOMMENDED Go Markdown library per
#                 Hugo's tooling team (Hugo migrated from
#                 blackfriday to goldmark in 2020).
#              2. AST-BASED — goldmark parses into a full
#                 Abstract Syntax Tree (vs pulldown-cmark's
#                 pull-event streaming).  AST gives extensions
#                 random-access to the document structure for
#                 transformations:
#                   import "github.com/yuin/goldmark"
#                   import "github.com/yuin/goldmark/parser"
#                   import "github.com/yuin/goldmark/renderer/html"
#                   md := goldmark.New(
#                     goldmark.WithExtensions(extension.GFM),
#                     goldmark.WithParserOptions(parser.WithAutoHeadingID()),
#                     goldmark.WithRendererOptions(html.WithUnsafe()),
#                   )
#                   var buf bytes.Buffer
#                   md.Convert([]byte(source), &buf)
#              3. EXTENSIBLE via Extender INTERFACE — goldmark's
#                 central design choice: extensions implement
#                 the Extender interface and register their
#                 own parsers / inline parsers / renderers /
#                 transformers.  Built-in extensions include:
#                   * extension.Table          — GFM tables
#                   * extension.Strikethrough  — ~~strikethrough~~
#                   * extension.TaskList       — - [ ] tasks
#                   * extension.Linkify        — autolinks
#                   * extension.DefinitionList — definition lists
#                   * extension.Footnote       — footnotes
#                   * extension.Typographer    — smart punctuation
#                   * extension.GFM            — all GFM at once
#                 Third-party extensions: mathjax, mermaid,
#                 highlight (syntax highlighting via Chroma),
#                 wikilinks, callouts, attributes, anchors,
#                 emoji.  Distinct from pulldown-cmark's
#                 Options-bitflags model (pulldown-cmark has
#                 fewer extension points; new features require
#                 forking).
#              4. PURE GO — no Cgo dependencies; works on all
#                 Go platforms without C toolchain.  Distinct
#                 from blackfriday which depends on C libraries
#                 in some code paths.
#              5. AUTO-HEADING-ID + AST INSPECTION — auto-
#                 generate slug IDs for headings; walk AST to
#                 collect TOC structure:
#                   parser.WithAutoHeadingID()
#                   ast.Walk(doc, func(n ast.Node, entering bool) {
#                     if h, ok := n.(*ast.Heading); ok && entering {
#                       fmt.Println(h.Level, string(h.Text(source)))
#                     }
#                     return ast.WalkContinue, nil
#                   })
#              6. AST-VISITOR PATTERN — `ast.Walk(root,
#                 walker_fn)` traverses the document; useful
#                 for custom transformations (link rewriting,
#                 footnote renumbering, etc.).  pulldown-cmark
#                 has no equivalent walker (uses iterator).
#              7. HTML SAFE BY DEFAULT — raw HTML in source is
#                 escaped unless `html.WithUnsafe()` is passed;
#                 distinct from blackfriday (raw HTML allowed
#                 by default).
#              8. RENDERER INTERFACE — custom renderers can
#                 emit JSON / LaTeX / RTF / etc. by
#                 implementing the Renderer interface.
#                 pulldown-cmark requires writing your own
#                 event loop.
#              9. NODE KIND REGISTRY — each AST node has a
#                 KIND type (KindHeading, KindParagraph,
#                 KindCodeBlock, KindFencedCodeBlock,
#                 KindBlockquote, KindList, KindListItem,
#                 KindLink, KindEmphasis, KindText, etc.) for
#                 type-safe AST navigation.
#             10. YUSUKE-INUZUKA / YUIN ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE
#                 — Yusuke Inuzuka (yuin) is a Japanese Go
#                 developer; also maintains:
#                   * yuin/goldmark      — Markdown parser     (THIS)
#                   * yuin/goldmark-meta — YAML front-matter ext
#                   * yuin/goldmark-highlighting — Chroma syntax highlight
#                   * yuin/gopher-lua    — Lua VM in Go
#                   * yuin/gluamapper    — Lua ↔ Go data conversion
#                   * yuin/stagger       — staggered batch processing
#                 Distinct maintainer ecosystem from Steve
#                 Francia (spf13/cobra/viper/afero), Sindre
#                 Sorhus, Mathew Roy (go-resty), fsnotify
#                 community, and others.)
# License: MIT (goldmark); GPL-2.0 (stitchmd)
# Status:  yuin/goldmark — 4,821+ stars on yuin/goldmark,
#          ~250M go.sum downloads (TOP-50 Go library by usage);
#          foundational Markdown library used by:
#            * Hugo (gohugoio/hugo — migrated from blackfriday
#              to goldmark in 2020)
#            * charmbracelet/glamour (TUI markdown renderer)
#            * gomarkdown/markdown (as renderer base)
#            * Caddy (some plugin docs)
#            * gitea (server-side markdown rendering)
#            * notebrew (static site CMS)
#            * stitchmd (THIS)
#            * 5000+ Go applications
#          stitchmd — 63+ stars on abhinav/stitchmd, used by
#          documentation teams maintaining multi-file
#          Markdown books.
#
